{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17653673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17653673"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:47:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18586"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18586"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.14,0.23,0.41,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11318"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79942"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11318","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11318"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18586"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65238"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10396"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26227"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26232"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79942","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79942"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EElectroencephalography (EEG) records electrical activity from the brain. Different wave patterns are associated with specific states of consciousness and brain activity.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes beta waves on EEG?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Very low frequency waves seen during meditation","Low-frequency high-amplitude waves seen during deep sleep","Medium-frequency waves seen during light sleep","High-frequency low-amplitude waves seen during alert consciousness","Very high frequency waves seen during seizures"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-frequency low-amplitude waves seen during alert consciousness\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes beta waves, which occur at 14-30 Hz. These waves are characteristic of the awake, alert brain engaged in active thinking, problem-solving, or focused attention. They are most prominent in the parietal and frontal regions of the cerebral cortex.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow-frequency high-amplitude waves seen during deep sleep\u003C/strong\u003E - These characteristics describe delta waves (0.5-4 Hz)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMedium-frequency waves seen during light sleep\u003C/strong\u003E - These characteristics describe theta waves (4-8 Hz)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVery low frequency waves seen during meditation\u003C/strong\u003E - This better describes alpha waves (8-13 Hz)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVery high frequency waves seen during seizures\u003C/strong\u003E - Seizure activity shows spike-and-wave discharges rather than a specific frequency band\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBeta waves represent cortical activation and are enhanced during cognitive tasks, anxiety states, and when maintaining focused attention. They are suppressed during movement and increased during tension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta waves (14-30 Hz) are high-frequency, low-amplitude brain waves associated with active, alert consciousness and cognitive processing.","Beta waves are predominantly recorded from the parietal and frontal regions during wakeful states.","Beta activity increases during mental tasks, anxiety, and focused attention."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65238"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18586"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65238","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65238"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-16T15:29:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-16T15:29:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11318"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79942"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"descript